I usually find myself using one of three methods:

1. `react-native-navigation` lets you define what happens on a screen focus:
```javascript
this.willFocusSubscription = this.props.navigation.addListener(
	&quot;willFocus&quot;,
	payload =&gt; {
		this.fetchData()
	}
)
```
This will trigger every time the user returns (or enters) the screen.

2. `FlatList` with `onRefresh`:
```javascript
&lt;FlatList
	data={this.state.data}
	onRefresh={() =&gt; {
	    this.onRefresh()
	}}
	refreshing={this.state.refreshing}
/&gt;
```

3. `componentDidMount` like yourself.

You should use AppState https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/appstate

When AppState change from other to `active` state, you could fetch new data.

```javascript
import React, {Component} from &#39;react&#39;;
import {AppState, Text} from &#39;react-native&#39;;

class AppStateExample extends Component {
  state = {
    appState: AppState.currentState,
  };

  componentDidMount() {
    AppState.addEventListener(&#39;change&#39;, this._handleAppStateChange);
  }

  componentWillUnmount() {
    AppState.removeEventListener(&#39;change&#39;, this._handleAppStateChange);
  }

  _handleAppStateChange = (nextAppState) =&gt; {
    if (
      this.state.appState.match(/inactive|background/) &amp;&amp;
      nextAppState === &#39;active&#39;
    ) {
      console.log(&#39;App has come to the foreground! Fetch new data?!&#39;);
    }
    this.setState({appState: nextAppState});
  };

  render() {
    return &lt;Text&gt;Current state is: {this.state.appState}&lt;/Text&gt;;
  }
}
```

